abstractNote|The COVID-19 pandemic caused radical temporary breaks with past energy use trends. How post-pandemic recovery will impact the longer-term energy transition is unclear. Here we present a set of global COVID-19 shock-and-recovery scenarios that systematically explore the effect of demand changes persisting. Our pathways project final energy demand reductions of 1–36 EJ yr−1 by 2025 and cumulative CO2 emission reductions of 14–45 GtCO2 by 2030. Uncertainty ranges depend on the depth and duration of the economic downturn and demand-side changes. Recovering from the pandemic with energy-efficient practices embedded in new patterns of travel, work, consumption and production reduces climate mitigation challenges. A low energy demand recovery reduces carbon prices for a 1.5 °C-consistent pathway by 19%, lowers energy supply investments until 2030 by US$1.8 trillion and softens the pressure to rapidly upscale renewable energy technologies.
新冠疫情导致了与过去能源使用趋势的根本性暂时性断裂。后疫情时期的恢复将如何影响更长期的能源转型目前尚不清楚。在这里，我们提出了一组全球COVID-19冲击与复苏情景，系统地探讨了持续的需求变化对影响的效果。我们的路径项目预计到2025年，最终能源需求将减少1-36 EJ/年，到2030年累积CO2排放将减少14-45 GtCO2。不确定性范围取决于经济衰退的深度和持续时间以及需求端的变化。通过将能源效率实践嵌入到新的出行、工作、消费和生产模式中，从疫情中恢复有助于降低气候缓解挑战。低能源需求的恢复将使1.5°C一致路径的碳价格下降19%，到2030年降低能源供应投资1.8万亿美元，并减轻了迅速扩大可再生能源技术的压力。
