opportunities towards a new normality or revert to energy system Climate mitigation scenarios with persistent 
COVID-19-related energy demand changesJarmo S. Kikstra1,2,3,9R
, Adriano Vinca1,4
,9, Francesco Lovat1, Benigna Boza-Kiss1,5, 
Bas van Ruijven1, Charlie Wilson1,6, Joeri Rogelj1,2,3, Behnam Zakeri

--- STREAM BREAK ---

1,7, Oliver Fricko1 and 
Keywan Riahi1,8The COVID-19 pandemic caused radical temporary breaks with past energy use trends. How post-pandemic recovery will 
impact the longer-term energy transition is unclear. Here we present a set of global COVID-19 shock-and-recovery scenarios 
that systematically explore the effect of demand changes persisting. Our pathways project final energy demand reductions 
of 136 EJyr1 by 2025 and cumulative CO2 emission reductions of 1445 GtCO2 by 2030. Uncertainty ranges depend on the 
depth and duration of the economic downturn and demand-side changes. Recovering from the pandemic with energy-efficient 
practices embedded in new patterns of travel, work, consumption and production reduces climate mitigation challenges. A low 
energy demand recovery reduces carbon prices for a 1.5°C-consistent pathway by 19%, lowers energy supply investments until 
2030 by US$1.8 trillion and softens the pressure to rapidly upscale renewable energy technologies.

